<p>Hi Mark,</p>

<p>I have completed my investigation on the <strong>AFOP_MFdsBreaks</strong> report and would like to share my findings for your review.</p>

<p>From my analysis, it appears that the original AFOP report developed by Lokesh was the first implementation of this report. While reviewing the original query, I noticed that it contains conditions such as <span class="code">sd.item_id IS NULL</span>, which seems to differ from the implementation used for the other departmental breaks reports. Based on the previous discussions and your earlier comments, this original query does not appear to align with the standard implementation used by the remaining department reports.</p>

<p>I then reviewed all of the existing departmental break reports (<strong>CA-Income, CA-Mand, CSG TP-D&amp;R, CSG TP-Sett, MFAO, MFS, SMF, TP-D&amp;R, TP-Sett and R&amp;A</strong>). All of these reports use the same query structure, with only the department name changing in the WHERE clause. Their report layouts, output columns, and report designs are also consistent.</p>

<p>I also verified the <strong>TLM_REF_REASON_CATEGORY</strong> table, where AFOP is listed along with the other department names. Based on this, my assumption is that <strong>AFOP should also be treated as another departmental breaks report</strong>, following the same implementation pattern as the other departments.</p>

<p>Based on this approach, I created a new Oracle query and a new BIRT report design for <strong>AFOP_MFdsBreaks</strong> by reusing the common departmental breaks query and changing only the department filter to <strong>AFOP</strong>.</p>

